118
00:08:34.970 --> 00:08:42.030
Thorin (Joe): But, the Ad Proto stuff is actually really cool. I want to explain it to you really quick, if I can bend your ear and info dump on you.

119
00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:44.009
Mike Hall: You guys okay with that? Yeah, I'm good for it.

120
00:08:44.010 --> 00:09:01.579
Thorin (Joe): Okay, so imagine a world where everybody has sort of a personal repository of data, call it a PDS, okay? And this is stuff that they can publish to the world, and it's all, strongly typed schemas, extensible, and,

121
00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:21.459
Thorin (Joe): And it's cryptographically signed to an identity so that it's your thing, and so you can hire companies to host this stuff for you, or you can self-host it. But essentially, you have this thing that is your data. And applications then use OAuth to actually ask, hey, can we write to your… can we manage a certain set of things in your data repository for you?

122
00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:23.129
Thorin (Joe): And,

123
00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:30.889
Thorin (Joe): and then they get permission to actually update and change and do things to stuff that's happening in your data repository, your PDS.

124
00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:48.689
Thorin (Joe): And then there's systems that actually go through and, like, when you publish a new thing to your PDS, you can notify systems so that they can actually update their views and actually read it. And then there's other systems out there that index all the PDSs out there and find links and backlinks, because everything has a strong identity, because it's all content indexed and all that.

125
00:09:48.690 --> 00:10:08.249
Thorin (Joe): That's essentially what AdProto is, and so, like, social media, like, you know, Twitter-like experiences are one thing where every post is one thing, every like is another thing, but you own your data, and nobody else… and you can take it with you and do other things, but you can do all sorts of other applications where they're actually writing to your data store on your behalf.

126
00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:11.809
Thorin (Joe): But ultimately, you're in control. That's kind of cool, isn't it?

127
00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:12.610
Mike Hall: Yeah.

128
00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:16.890
Mike Hall: It's better than… it's better than what we have now, which is we're the product.

129
00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:28.359
Ben Pfaff: I think time will tell whether that more centralized system of App Proto versus the less centralized system of ActivityPub will win out in the end, but App Proto definitely has the money behind it.

130
00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:32.310
Thorin (Joe): Well, I mean, there's not that much money in any of this stuff, let's be clear.

131
00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:35.299
Ben Pfaff: Well, there's a lot of investment in it, anyway.

132
00:10:35.300 --> 00:10:40.849
Thorin (Joe): The problem with ActivityPub and Mastodon in general is that, number one is that, like, it's…

133
00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:57.809
Thorin (Joe): it's fundamentally, like, about Mastodon, and there is not this larger thing of things that get published onto ActivityPub, right? It's not a more generic thing. And then the other thing is that it's centered on servers, not on people. So, like, if your server admin, if your server shuts down, you're just kind of screwed.

134
00:10:58.300 --> 00:11:02.109
Thorin (Joe): And there's no way to migrate your stuff, really, from one server to another.

135
00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:07.340
Thorin (Joe): You can migrate some of it, but not all of it, and so it ends up being kind of wacky.

136
00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:08.400
